HEADWORD: Sprag
<hw>Sprag</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Spray</er> a branch.]</ety>
<def>A billet of wood; a piece of timber used as a prop.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sprag</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sprag
<hw>Sprag</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Spragged</conjf> <pr>(spr⟦acr⟧gd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Spragging</conjf> <pr>(-g⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To check the motion of, as a carriage on a steep grade,
by putting a sprag between the spokes of the wheel.</def> <rj><au>R. S.
Poole.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To prop or sustain with a sprag.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sprag</ent>⟦br⟧

